ick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places called Barlow, especially those in Lancashire and Yorkshire. The former is named with Old English <i>bere</i> ‘barley’ + <i>hlāw</i> ‘hill’; the latter probably has as its first element the derived adjective <i>beren</i> or the compound <i>bere-ærn</i> ‘barn’. There is also a place of this name in Derbyshire, named with Old English <i>bār</i> ‘boar’ or <i>bere</i> ‘barley’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’, and one in Shropshire, which is from <i>bere</i> ‘barley’ + <i>lēah</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Barlowe","meanings":["English: variant of   Barlow  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":10,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":19,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Barlow was born in 1318, in Barlow by Manchester, Lancashire, England, his father, Sir Thomas Barlow, was 19 and his mother, Anne Stanwidge, was 15. He married Agnes Entwhistle. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1359, in England, at the age of 41."},"et":{"1318–1359":"1318–1359","1330–1388":"1330–1388","1330–1350":"1330–1350","1350–1400":"1350–1400","1299–1350":"1299–1350","1303–Female":"1303–Surnud","1359":"1359","1337":"1337","1303":"1303","1400":"1400","1388":"1388","1453":"1453","1299":"1299","1330":"1330","1350":"1350","1318":"1318","1328":"1328","Barlow by Manchester, Lancashire, England":"Barlow by Manchester, Lancashire, England","Chorlton Upon Medlock, Lancashire, England":"Chorlton-on-Medlock, Manchester, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Barlow Hall, Barlow, Manchester, Lancashire, England":"Manchester, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"1318–1359":"1318–1359","1330–1388":"1330–1388","1330–1350":"1330–1350","1350–1400":"1350–1400","1299–1350":"1299–1350","1303–Female":"1303–Kuollut","1359":"1359","1337":"1337","1303":"1303","1400":"1400","1388":"1388","1453":"1453","1299":"1299","1330":"1330","1350":"1350","1318":"1318","1328":"1328","Barlow by Manchester, Lancashire, England":"Barlow by Manchester, Lancashire, England","Chorlton Upon Medlock, Lancashire, England":"Chorlton-on-Medlock, Manchester, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"England","Barlow Hall, Barlow, Manchester, Lancashire, England":"Manchester, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England"},"fr":{"1318–1359